1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:29,565
Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:30,760 --> 00:00:38,984
So we're covering equanimity this evening, and I think that completes the four illimitables, maybe.

3
00:00:39,143 --> 00:00:40,548
I'm not so sure I've done compassion.

4
00:00:40,728 --> 00:00:42,173
Well, I'll get around to it if I haven't.

5
00:00:43,256 --> 00:00:45,241
So equanimity...

6
00:00:46,082 --> 00:01:00,281
According to Jnana Poniketera, who was the German founding monk of the Buddhist Publication Society, to which Bhikkhu Bodhi then became the editor, he's got a massive collection of books on Buddhism.

7
00:01:01,023 --> 00:01:05,868
He wrote what is still a classic, The Heart of Buddhist Meditation, well worth a read.

8
00:01:06,370 --> 00:01:10,334
He was a follower of the Mahasi, like myself.

9
00:01:10,314 --> 00:01:13,441
And he wrote another book called The Vision of the Dharma.

10
00:01:13,641 --> 00:01:18,069
And in it, he states that equanimity is the most important of all virtues.

11
00:01:19,031 --> 00:01:19,632
And I agree.

12
00:01:19,653 --> 00:01:24,543
Now, first of all, we have to understand what equanimity is.

13
00:01:25,084 --> 00:01:29,572
And I might extend the meaning of it just a little bit.

14
00:01:30,143 --> 00:01:34,548
So synonyms are things like composure, calmness.

15
00:01:37,391 --> 00:01:44,438
It's got this word animus in the middle of it, and that's a Latin word which covers both the heart and the mind.

16
00:01:45,259 --> 00:01:49,683
So in Buddhism, remember, when feeling arises, perception arises.

17
00:01:49,743 --> 00:01:52,206
When perception arises, feelings arises.

18
00:01:52,326 --> 00:01:56,210
So the intellect and the emotional life are always working together.

19
00:01:56,510 --> 00:01:57,972
This is the point, yeah?

20
00:01:57,953 --> 00:02:12,986
So what equanimity would ask us to do is not to hold on to opinions, see them more as perspectives so we're open to other people's and undermine the sense of, well, I'm right and everybody's wrong.

21
00:02:13,247 --> 00:02:15,372
That's that sort of position.

22
00:02:15,705 --> 00:02:22,078
From the heart's point of view, you're overcoming things like acquisitiveness, aversion, fear, preference.

23
00:02:22,538 --> 00:02:31,395
So now if we think of a judge, we definitely don't want him to fall to the victim of bribery and all sorts of personal gain.

24
00:02:32,497 --> 00:02:36,786
We don't want her to be swayed by the clever arguments of the lawyers.

25
00:02:36,765 --> 00:02:39,870
We don't want her to be afraid of threats.

26
00:02:40,811 --> 00:02:48,942
We don't want him or her to be biased towards the accused because they just don't like them.

27
00:02:50,383 --> 00:02:55,509
And they've no reference as to what the verdict of the jury comes up with.

28
00:02:56,510 --> 00:03:02,679
So they must maintain a sense of composure, unruffled poise.

29
00:03:03,060 --> 00:03:04,782
So this is equanimity.

30
00:03:07,090 --> 00:03:17,754
Now, if we look at something like climate crisis, so equanimity would stop us from becoming panicking preppers, right?

31
00:03:17,914 --> 00:03:19,658
Imagining terrible scenarios.

32
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:25,453
I mean, frankly, what's happening now doesn't need the imagination so much, lead much to the imagination.

33
00:03:25,585 --> 00:03:28,968
We don't get angry with deniers, right?

34
00:03:29,889 --> 00:03:35,037
And we help to maintain an attitude of whatever the outcome is so that we keep to our principles.

35
00:03:35,597 --> 00:03:45,289
So Noreen has done a set of writings on the maxims, which relate to situations which are desperate.

36
00:03:46,591 --> 00:03:53,639
In such a situation, we remain calm, tranquil, stiff upper lip, that sort of thing.

37
00:03:54,420 --> 00:03:55,322
Not so stiff, Mike.

38
00:03:57,326 --> 00:04:12,798
So when we look at where it's important, it stops all the social virtues from falling into the error of their near enemy.

39
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:17,648
So love has its obvious enemy, has hatred.

40
00:04:17,627 --> 00:04:19,934
But its near enemy, of course, is attachment.

41
00:04:20,855 --> 00:04:24,204
And what equanimity is supposed to do is to stop you doing that way.

42
00:04:24,223 --> 00:04:29,055
So equanimity, as it were, is subsisting all our virtues.

43
00:04:29,357 --> 00:04:33,848
If it's not there, we slip into these subtle errors.

44
00:04:33,827 --> 00:04:44,867
Compassion, the obvious enemy is cruelty, but the subtle enemy is having pity for giving preference to somebody whom you have more pity for than for somebody else.

45
00:04:45,288 --> 00:04:54,384
So if you were a nurse or a doctor or a teacher, even then, of course, you'd upset other people by giving other people preferential treatment.

46
00:04:56,692 --> 00:05:05,985
When it comes to joy, one of the obvious enemies is jealousy, of course, because we're supposed to rejoice in the joy in the success of others.

47
00:05:07,446 --> 00:05:11,632
But the subtle enemy would be to sort of over-egg it, to get all excited.

48
00:05:11,672 --> 00:05:20,101
And again, equanimity calms us down, keeps us on the steady path, keeps the joy true to its object.

49
00:05:20,588 --> 00:05:23,711
And finally, there's equanimity itself.

50
00:05:24,271 --> 00:05:28,076
And of course, that also has an enemy, a subtle enemy.

51
00:05:28,096 --> 00:05:35,966
The obvious enemy, of course, is to become completely unruffled, to lose your composure, and that would be it.

52
00:05:36,706 --> 00:05:39,451
The subtle enemy is indifference.

53
00:05:39,471 --> 00:05:43,615
So we think we're being equanimous, but actually we're being indifferent.

54
00:05:43,636 --> 00:05:45,338
We're being apathetic.

55
00:05:45,517 --> 00:05:48,081
We're not really caring.

56
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:54,031
So what we do for that is depending on the situation, we raise the social virtue.

57
00:05:54,312 --> 00:05:57,497
So if it needs friendship, you raise love.

58
00:05:57,918 --> 00:06:02,627
If it needs compassion or caring nature, you raise compassion, etc.

59
00:06:03,146 --> 00:06:24,559
So the equanimity is something that subsists all the other virtues, stops, for instance, courage falling into foolhardiness, humility dipping into this sort of false self-effacement, a sort of humbly humbleness, and keeps us cool.

60
00:06:24,819 --> 00:06:29,766
It keeps us cool, it keeps us poised, but it also keeps us warm.

61
00:06:29,786 --> 00:06:31,007
It keeps us engaged.

62
00:06:31,569 --> 00:06:31,668
Okay.

63
00:06:32,999 --> 00:06:45,696
There was an occasion when I was at two monasteries, they'd happen one after the other, actually, where I was with one monk and there was a cat in the room, had obviously been playing around with a mouse and killed it.

64
00:06:45,716 --> 00:06:48,279
So I just said, did you try and stop that?

65
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:52,105
And he said, no, it's cat karma and mouse karma.

66
00:06:52,252 --> 00:06:58,100
And I went to another monastery later on, and this cat just jumped out and jumped on this bird.

67
00:06:58,302 --> 00:07:00,925
And this monk got up and gave the cat a great wallop.

68
00:07:01,987 --> 00:07:04,009
Unfortunately, he didn't save the little bird.

69
00:07:04,050 --> 00:07:04,951
The bird died.

70
00:07:05,011 --> 00:07:14,966
And he very beautifully held it up by the wings and chanted, all compounded things arise and pass away.

71
00:07:15,666 --> 00:07:19,391
So which one had equanimity, you see?

72
00:07:20,872 --> 00:07:24,096
So now where we another place we find equanimity.

73
00:07:24,276 --> 00:07:27,220
So that's equanimity with social virtues, our engagement.

74
00:07:27,759 --> 00:07:30,343
Another place, of course, is in the factors of enlightenment.

75
00:07:30,903 --> 00:07:38,391
So all these facts of enlightenment are supporting sati, the main one, supporting right awareness.

76
00:07:38,591 --> 00:07:41,995
And we have these qualities which balance each other.

77
00:07:42,255 --> 00:07:44,517
So we have a sense of focus.

78
00:07:44,497 --> 00:07:48,956
sense of steadiness of attention, and that needs right effort.

79
00:07:49,117 --> 00:07:50,963
So too much effort, you get restless.

80
00:07:51,125 --> 00:07:54,458
Too little effort, the mind begins to wander.

81
00:07:56,310 --> 00:08:05,403
And then you have this pair of, well, the word piti is translated as joy, but it's the joy of interest, right?

82
00:08:05,423 --> 00:08:11,112
Just like when you're exploring anything, when you're interested in anything, that's a joyous mental state.

83
00:08:11,814 --> 00:08:14,177
And that needs calmness, right?

84
00:08:14,697 --> 00:08:17,401
Again, it stops the interest becoming excited.

85
00:08:18,023 --> 00:08:19,985
So too much calmness, you fall asleep.

86
00:08:20,206 --> 00:08:24,192
Too little calmness, you get all excited and restless.

87
00:08:24,172 --> 00:08:41,842
And then the final two are the investigation of the Dharma, which, when you're sitting, are the three characteristics of existence, which is, you know, impermanence, how we create suffering for ourselves, the dukkha, and not-self, insubstantiality.

88
00:08:41,822 --> 00:08:44,768
And that's balanced with equanimity.

89
00:08:45,008 --> 00:08:49,395
So it stops us trying to see something.

90
00:08:49,897 --> 00:08:53,202
It stops us over-efforting and it keeps us cool.

91
00:08:53,302 --> 00:08:57,570
It keeps us objective in our investigation.

92
00:08:59,490 --> 00:09:02,133
Okay, so that's the seven factors.

93
00:09:02,153 --> 00:09:11,562
So when it comes to vipassana, whenever we practice vipassana, as we'll do tonight a little bit, there has to be this quality of equanimity.

94
00:09:11,721 --> 00:09:17,807
And you'll notice that in those seven factors of enlightenment, there isn't any love, there isn't any compassion.

95
00:09:18,307 --> 00:09:26,534
We can presume that that's there as an underlying purpose because we want to escape suffering.

96
00:09:26,674 --> 00:09:29,498
So that's an act of compassion towards ourselves.

97
00:09:29,477 --> 00:09:33,846
But it's not directly involved in the process of insight.

98
00:09:34,667 --> 00:09:38,234
But in Vipassana, we have this upeka, right?

99
00:09:38,714 --> 00:09:39,855
This equanimity.

100
00:09:40,498 --> 00:09:45,866
Now, again, if we get up from a practice and we go straight into daily life,

101
00:09:45,846 --> 00:09:51,658
then the danger of upeka falling towards its near enemy is there, right?

102
00:09:51,739 --> 00:09:57,971
So it becomes a sort of aloofness, an inability to fully engage.

103
00:09:58,493 --> 00:10:00,697
And the way we overcome that is by doing metta.

104
00:10:01,418 --> 00:10:03,163
So in ordinary daily life,

105
00:10:03,143 --> 00:10:15,022
After you've done your hour or two hour meditation in the morning, you then bring to mind the people whom you're going to visit, you're going to meet during the day, and you offer them this loving kindness.

106
00:10:15,322 --> 00:10:19,008
And especially to those whom you're having some problems with, right?

107
00:10:19,028 --> 00:10:23,514
And of course, you do it again in the night after your two to three hour meditation session.

108
00:10:25,739 --> 00:10:32,346
Finally, there's the four worldly conditions, sometimes referred to as the four worldly wins.

109
00:10:33,148 --> 00:10:39,355
Gain and loss, disrepute and fame, blame and praise, pleasure and pain.

110
00:10:40,738 --> 00:10:44,763
So when it comes to gain and loss, sometimes you win and sometimes you lose.

111
00:10:45,003 --> 00:10:53,433
I mean, playing games at school really helps us to become acquainted with those two mental states.

112
00:10:53,413 --> 00:11:20,231
and um the thing is uh what equanimity does it doesn't it stops getting excited about gaining too much and it and we don't get depressed when we lose it's a it's a sort of a way of being unruffled uh it's not a it it sort of stops us overreacting that's all so um when the buddha for instance was asked how did he feel when uh

113
00:11:20,211 --> 00:11:24,217
Somebody rejected his teaching, or at least didn't respond to his teaching.

114
00:11:24,317 --> 00:11:25,078
He said it was fine.

115
00:11:25,620 --> 00:11:29,666
You know, according to him, it was the person's karma, right?

116
00:11:30,386 --> 00:11:33,390
But when somebody actually did follow, he said he felt joy.

117
00:11:33,792 --> 00:11:39,519
So that's that sympathetic joy, the joy of knowing that somebody was on the path to liberation.

118
00:11:40,933 --> 00:11:48,422
When it comes to having a fame or infamy, a good reputation, we all want a good reputation.

119
00:11:48,442 --> 00:11:54,349
We all want people to have a feeling that we're good people, that they respect us, etc.

120
00:11:54,808 --> 00:12:02,778
And when we find somebody's, you know, slipped us a little slander, said things that even if it's only a small thing, we find it humiliating.

121
00:12:02,998 --> 00:12:05,902
You know, we get angry about it and we do the same to them.

122
00:12:06,522 --> 00:12:08,183
But equanimity stops you doing that.

123
00:12:08,224 --> 00:12:09,546
You see, you just accept it.

124
00:12:09,725 --> 00:12:10,907
That's the way it is.

125
00:12:10,886 --> 00:12:15,032
And we try not to fall into that error ourselves, of course.

126
00:12:16,274 --> 00:12:27,268
At that time, they used to have these meetings on the full moon night, which were sort of debates between the various teachers and philosophers, the Brahmins.

127
00:12:28,568 --> 00:12:31,994
And seemingly that was the big night out.

128
00:12:32,173 --> 00:12:36,919
I mean, this is before reading and writing, radio, TV, internet.

129
00:12:37,461 --> 00:12:40,083
I mean, what did people do before all that?

130
00:12:40,267 --> 00:12:46,918
Well, they used to, in the East anyway, they'd gather on a full moon night and listen to these talks.

131
00:12:48,259 --> 00:12:55,152
So the Buddha warned his monastics anyway, not to get involved in these events.

132
00:12:55,793 --> 00:12:58,376
And this is some of the verses that he tells them.

133
00:12:59,486 --> 00:13:04,794
Desiring debate, they plunge into an assembly where each takes the other as a fool.

134
00:13:05,556 --> 00:13:11,544
Relying on others, they state their contention, desiring praise while claiming to be experts.

135
00:13:12,586 --> 00:13:19,476
Addicted to debating in the midst of an assembly, their need for praise makes them nervous.

136
00:13:20,798 --> 00:13:23,322
But when they're repudiated, they get embarrassed.

137
00:13:23,763 --> 00:13:27,469
Upset at criticism, they find fault in others.

138
00:13:28,072 --> 00:13:37,101
In their doctrine, if their doctrine is said to be weak, the judges declare it repudiated, the loser weeps and wails, moaning, they beat me.

139
00:13:38,023 --> 00:13:46,410
When these arguments come up amongst ascetics, they get excited or dejected, seeing this refrain from contention.

140
00:13:46,831 --> 00:13:49,494
The only purpose is fame and profit.

141
00:13:50,434 --> 00:13:54,739
There's a Buddha telling us not to get involved in these argumentations.

142
00:13:56,001 --> 00:13:58,826
The next one would be blame and praise.

143
00:13:59,206 --> 00:14:05,856
Now, whenever you get blamed, even if it is your fault, it's not very nice.

144
00:14:06,037 --> 00:14:07,158
It hurts.

145
00:14:07,379 --> 00:14:07,840
You see what I mean?

146
00:14:08,640 --> 00:14:14,168
Actually speaking, when something goes wrong, we shouldn't be blaming people.

147
00:14:14,409 --> 00:14:17,214
You know, we should be asking, how did it happen?

148
00:14:17,474 --> 00:14:17,875
Right.

149
00:14:17,855 --> 00:14:23,346
What we're looking for is a solution so that that particular incident doesn't happen again.

150
00:14:25,029 --> 00:14:35,491
For instance, we had an occasion, we've had, I think, two of our rice cookers, what do they call them?

151
00:14:35,471 --> 00:14:43,501
Yeah, rice cookers ruined because the bowl wasn't inside and the assistant just put the food straight into the cooker.

152
00:14:43,842 --> 00:14:47,067
So it went everywhere right into the machinery, into the electrics.

153
00:14:47,366 --> 00:14:48,749
We tried to save both of them.

154
00:14:49,049 --> 00:14:49,811
It was impossible.

155
00:14:50,511 --> 00:14:54,976
So now recognizing that that mistake is done, it's easy to do.

156
00:14:55,437 --> 00:14:57,801
We now leave an empty bowl.

157
00:14:57,780 --> 00:15:23,586
next to the to the cooker so that when the other bowl is taken out to be washed and the person comes in they recognize that there's no bowl in the cooker and that and so far so good right so we've got to keep our fingers crossed on that so there's no good blaming people you have to find out how the mistake was made how the how how it came about and then you just correct it as simple as that

158
00:15:23,566 --> 00:15:29,177
Anyway, on this business of praise and blame, there's a story of a Zen monk.

159
00:15:29,578 --> 00:15:30,600
So he entered a village.

160
00:15:30,681 --> 00:15:31,602
He was a local monk.

161
00:15:31,643 --> 00:15:35,491
He lived in his own little hut somewhere, and he came into the village for alms.

162
00:15:35,552 --> 00:15:39,921
Suddenly, this young woman accused him of making her pregnant.

163
00:15:39,900 --> 00:15:42,504
He was silent when the baby was born.

164
00:15:43,004 --> 00:15:47,571
They took it to his dwelling and he received it without saying anything.

165
00:15:47,831 --> 00:15:48,572
And he nurtured it.

166
00:15:48,932 --> 00:15:54,620
Well, of course, over time, especially the young woman wanting her baby back, the truth came out.

167
00:15:55,022 --> 00:16:01,370
So all the villagers went back and apologized and took the baby back and he gave it to them and he never said a word.

168
00:16:01,850 --> 00:16:06,297
So that's how we that's how we can deal with praise and blame.

169
00:16:07,019 --> 00:16:09,202
The final one, of course, is pleasure and pain.

170
00:16:09,222 --> 00:16:12,909
So we're always seeking pleasures and we're always trying to get away from pain.

171
00:16:13,551 --> 00:16:20,263
And these days, you know, with our consumerism and all that and our adverts always wanting to make us excited.

172
00:16:21,426 --> 00:16:22,748
Basically, we just want more.

173
00:16:22,768 --> 00:16:23,809
It doesn't matter what it is.

174
00:16:23,830 --> 00:16:25,432
We just want more of it.

175
00:16:25,413 --> 00:16:30,041
And so we tend to get lost in that sort of greediness.

176
00:16:30,682 --> 00:16:36,250
But that doesn't mean to say that we shouldn't appreciate a joy when it arises or a pleasure when it arises.

177
00:16:36,650 --> 00:16:40,638
But the trick, of course, is to remind ourselves that it's over.

178
00:16:40,857 --> 00:16:41,198
It's gone.

179
00:16:41,239 --> 00:16:41,700
It's finished.

180
00:16:41,759 --> 00:16:43,001
It cannot be repeated.

181
00:16:43,101 --> 00:16:43,822
This is the big thing.

182
00:16:44,224 --> 00:16:45,745
You can't repeat a joy.

183
00:16:46,206 --> 00:16:48,811
Make it something like it, but you can't repeat it.

184
00:16:49,211 --> 00:16:50,232
So you just let go of it.

185
00:16:50,333 --> 00:16:50,754
That's it.

186
00:16:50,774 --> 00:16:51,235
It's fine.

187
00:16:53,307 --> 00:17:00,393
And what equanimity does, of course, is it stops these unnecessary reactions.

188
00:17:01,835 --> 00:17:04,076
It rides on acceptance.

189
00:17:04,696 --> 00:17:05,698
This is the way it is.

190
00:17:06,018 --> 00:17:07,579
Things arise and pass away.

191
00:17:07,619 --> 00:17:09,501
You can't repeat anything.

192
00:17:10,542 --> 00:17:12,624
A joy will come and a joy passes.

193
00:17:13,625 --> 00:17:22,053
If I remember Blake's little phrase, to kiss a joy as it flies is to live in eternity's sunrise.

194
00:17:22,573 --> 00:17:23,314
Well, that's the trick.

195
00:17:23,294 --> 00:17:33,146
So we have a little verse here from the Buddha telling us about this, the four worldly conditions or winds.

196
00:17:33,768 --> 00:17:39,935
Gain does not obsess their minds and loss does not obsess their mind.

197
00:17:40,556 --> 00:17:47,125
Fame does not obsess their mind and disrepute does not obsess their mind.

198
00:17:47,105 --> 00:17:52,752
Blame does not obsess their mind and praise does not obsess their mind.

199
00:17:53,173 --> 00:17:58,842
Pleasure does not obsess their mind and pain does not obsess their minds.

200
00:17:59,221 --> 00:18:02,807
They're not attracted to gain or repelled by loss.

201
00:18:03,468 --> 00:18:07,294
They're not attracted to fame or repelled by disrepute.

202
00:18:07,954 --> 00:18:11,559
They're not attracted to praise or repelled by blame.

203
00:18:12,198 --> 00:18:15,721
They're not attracted to pleasure or repelled by pain.

204
00:18:16,962 --> 00:18:19,025
Not attracted to pleasure or repelled by pain.

205
00:18:19,885 --> 00:18:32,859
Having thus discarded attraction and repulsion, they are freed from birth, from old age and death, from sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and anguish.

206
00:18:33,299 --> 00:18:35,843
They are freed from suffering, I say.

207
00:18:37,425 --> 00:18:55,536
So having gone through these qualities, the quality of equanimity, how it's part of the seven facts of enlightenment, how we use it in our vipassana practice and these four worldly winds, how do we actually develop it as an exercise?

208
00:18:55,516 --> 00:18:57,278
So very much the same as metta.

209
00:18:57,377 --> 00:18:59,039
In fact, exactly the same as metta.

210
00:18:59,579 --> 00:19:06,748
You have certain well-wishings and you offer it to a benefactor and so on and so forth.

211
00:19:06,768 --> 00:19:08,369
And that's what I thought we would do now.

